{response.text}\"\n        )\n\n    data = response.json()\n\n    # ---- API\u2011level status check --------------------------------------------\n    if data.get(\"status\") != \"OK\":\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\n            \"Google Maps API returned an error\",\n            f\"API status: {data.get('status')}, message: {data.get('error_message')}\"\n        )\n\n    # If everything is fine, return the useful part of the payload\n    return data[\"routes\"][0]   # or whatever slice you need\n# -----------------------------------------------------------------\n```\n\n**Key points in the corrected version**\n\n* **Two\u2011argument raise** everywhere (`error_message`, `error_detail`).  \n* **`error_detail`** contains the raw HTTP response or exception string \u2013 very handy for debugging.  \n* A **`try/except`** block catches network\u2011level errors and re\u2011raises them as `HolidayAgentException`.  \n* The function returns a clean dictionary (you can adapt the return shape to your needs).\n\n---\n\n## \ud83e\udded If you still see the error\n\n1. **Double\u2011check the import path** \u2013 make sure you edited the *same* `HolidayAgentException` class that `GoogleMap.py` imports.  \n2. **Search the whole repo** for `HolidayAgentException(` to see if any other raise statements are missing the second argument.  \n3. **Run the script with a minimal test**:\n\n```python\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    # Use dummy values \u2013 you only need to hit the error path\n    try:\n        get_route(\"nowhere\", \"nowhere\", \"FAKE_KEY\")\n    except HolidayAgentException as e:\n        print(\"Caught:\", e, \"| detail:\", e.detail)\n```\n\nIf the script prints the message and the detail without throwing a `TypeError`, the fix is successful.\n\n---\n\n## \ud83d\udcde Need further assistance?\n\n* **Share the exact snippet** around line\u202f13 if you\u2019re unsure how to edit it.  \n* **Tell me where the exception class lives** (file name) if you want a pre