Exception(\"Google Maps request failed\", \"Timeout after 10\u202fs\")\n```\n\n---\n\n## \ud83d\udcc2 Typical location of the problematic line  \n\nBelow is a **common pattern** for a Google\u2011Maps helper. The error is most likely on the `raise` line.\n\n```python\nimport requests\nfrom ..exceptions import HolidayAgentException   # <-- where the class lives\n\ndef get_directions(origin, destination, api_key):\n    url = (\n        \"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/directions/json\"\n        f\"?origin={origin}&destination={destination}&key={api_key}\"\n    )\n    response = requests.get(url, timeout=10)\n\n    # <-- LINE 13 (or very close) \u2013 this is where the exception is raised\n    if response.status_code != 200:\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\n            \"Google Maps request failed\",\n            f\"Status {response.status_code}: {response.text}\"\n        )\n    # ... further processing ...\n```\n\nIf your file looks similar, just add the second argument (or change the exception class as shown above).\n\n---\n\n## \u2705 Step\u2011by\u2011step checklist to resolve the error\n\n| Step | Action | Why |\n|------|--------|-----|\n| **1\ufe0f\u20e3 Open the file** | `C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py` | You need to edit the line that raises the exception. |\n| **2\ufe0f\u20e3 Find line\u202f13** | Look for `raise HolidayAgentException` (or any call to that class). | That line is currently passing only one argument. |\n| **3\ufe0f\u20e3 Add the missing argument** | Either supply a detail string (`\"some detail\"`), `None`, or `\"\"`. | Satisfies the constructor signature. |\n| **4\ufe0f\u20e3 (Optional) Make the class flexible** | Edit the exception class to give `error_detail` a default value (`None`). | Prevents the same mistake elsewhere. |\n| **5\ufe0f\u20e3 Run a quick test** | Execute the function that calls Google Maps (use a valid API key). | Confirms the error is gone and the function works. |\n| **6\