uter handler).\n\n---\n\n### 2\ufe0f\u20e3 Make `error_detail` optional in the exception class (more future\u2011proof)\n\nIf you prefer to be able to raise the exception with **one** or **two** arguments everywhere, change the class definition (usually in `exceptions.py` or a similar module) to give `error_detail` a default value.\n\n```python\n# ---- ORIGINAL -------------------------------------------------\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail):\n        super().__init__(error_message)\n        self.detail = error_detail\n\n# ---- UPDATED \u2013 error_detail is optional -----------------------\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail=None):\n        super().__init__(error_message)\n        self.detail = error_detail\n```\n\nNow both of these are valid:\n\n```python\nraise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps request failed\")\nraise HolidayAgentException(\"Google Maps request failed\", \"Timeout after 10\u202fs\")\n```\n\n---\n\n## \ud83d\udcc2 Typical code around line\u202f13 (what you probably have)\n\nBelow is a **minimal, corrected** version of a Google\u2011Maps helper that shows the proper raise statements.\n\n```python\n# --------------------------------------------------------------\n# C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py\n# --------------------------------------------------------------\nimport logging\nimport requests\nfrom ..exceptions import HolidayAgentException   # adjust import if needed\n\ndef get_route(origin: str, destination: str, api_key: str) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Calls Google Directions API and returns the first route.\n    Raises HolidayAgentException with a helpful detail string on any failure.\n    \"\"\"\n    url = (\n        \"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/directions/json\"\n        f\"?origin={origin}&destination={destination}&key={api_key}\"\n    )\n    try:\n        response = requests.