s.RequestException as exc:\n        # Network\u2011level problem (DNS, timeout, etc.)\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\n            "Unable to reach Google Maps API",\n            str(exc)\n        ) from exc\n\n    # -----------------------------------------------------------------\n    # LINE 13 (or very close) – this is where the original error occurs\n    # -----------------------------------------------------------------\n    if response.status_code != 200:\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\n            "Google Maps request failed",\n            f"HTTP {response.status_code}: {response.text}"\n        )\n\n    data = response.json()\n\n    if data.get("status") != "OK":\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\n            "Google Maps API returned an error",\n            f"API status: {data.get(\'status\')}, message: {data.get(\'error_message\')}"\n        )\n\n    # Return the useful part of the payload (adjust as needed)\n    return data["routes"][0]\n```\n\n**Key points**\n\n* **Two\u2011argument raise** everywhere (`error_message`, `error_detail`).  \n* `error_detail` contains the raw HTTP response or the caught exception string – very handy for debugging.  \n* A `try/except` block catches low\u2011level network errors and re\u2011raises them as `HolidayAgentException`.  \n\n---\n\n## \U0001f6e0\ufe0f Step\u2011by\u2011step checklist to get the script running again\n\n| # | Action | Command / Code |\n|---|--------|----------------|\n| **1** | Open the file | `code C:\\AI_2026\\Projects\\1_TravelBot\\HolidayAgent\\Tools\\GoogleMap.py` (or your preferred editor) |\n| **2** | Locate line\u202f13 | Search for `raise HolidayAgentException` |\n| **3** | Add the missing argument (or use the optional\u2011argument fix) | See the examples above |\n| **4** | (Optional) Edit the exception class to make `error_detail` optional | Find `class HolidayAgentException` and add `error_detail=None` |\n| **5** | Save the file |\n| **6** | Run a quick sanity test (replace