\n---\\n\\n### 2\ufe0f\u20e3 Make `error_detail` optional in the exception class (more future\u2011proof)\\n\\nIf you prefer to be able to raise the exception with **one** or **two** arguments everywhere, change the class definition (usually in `exceptions.py` or a similar module) to give `error_detail` a default value.\\n\\n```python\\n# ---- ORIGINAL -------------------------------------------------\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n\\n# ---- UPDATED \u2013 error_detail is optional -----------------------\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    def __init__(self, error_message, error_detail=None):\\n        super().__init__(error_message)\\n        self.detail = error_detail\\n```\\n\\nNow both of these are valid:\\n\\n```python\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\\"Google Maps request failed\\\")\\nraise HolidayAgentException(\\\"Google Maps request failed\\\", \\\"Timeout after 10\u202fs\\\")\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udcc2 Typical code around line\u202f13 (what you probably have)\\n\\nBelow is a **minimal, corrected** version of a Google\u2011Maps helper that shows the proper raise statements.\\n\\n```python\\n# --------------------------------------------------------------\\n# C:\\\\AI_2026\\\\Projects\\\\1_TravelBot\\\\HolidayAgent\\\\Tools\\\\GoogleMap.py\\n# --------------------------------------------------------------\\nimport logging\\nimport requests\\nfrom ..exceptions import HolidayAgentException   # adjust import if needed\\n\\ndef get_route(origin: str, destination: str, api_key: str) -> dict:\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Calls Google Directions API and returns the first route.\\n    Raises HolidayAgentException with a helpful detail string on any failure.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    url = (\\n        \\\"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/directions/json\\\"\\n        f\\\"?origin={origin}&destination={destination}&key={api_key}\\\"\\n    )\\n    try:\\n        response = requests.get(url, timeout=10)\\n    except requests.RequestException as exc:\\n        # Network\u2011level problem (DNS, timeout, etc.)\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            \\\"Unable to reach Google Maps API\\\",\\n            str(exc)\\n        ) from exc\\n\\n    # -----------------------------------------------------------------\\n    # LINE 13 (or very close) \u2013 this is where the original error occurs\\n    # -----------------------------------------------------------------\\n    if response.status_code != 200:\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            \\\"Google Maps request failed\\\",\\n            f\\\"HTTP {response.status_code}: {response.text}\\\"\\n        )\\n\\n    data = response.json()\\n\\n    if data.get(\\\"status\\\") != \\\"OK\\\":\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            \\\"Google Maps API returned an error\\\",\\n            f\\\"API status: {data.get('status')}, message: {data.get('error_message')}\\\"\\n        )\\n\\n    # Return the useful part of the payload (adjust as needed)\\n    return data[\\\"routes\\\"][0]\\n```\\n\\n**Key points**\\n\\n* **Two\u2011argument raise** everywhere (`error_message`, `error_detail`).  \\n* `error_detail` contains the raw HTTP response or the caught exception string \u2013 very handy for debugging.  \\n* A `try/except` block catches low\u2011level network errors and re\u2011raises them as `HolidayAgentException`.  \\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Step\u2011by\u2011step checklist to get the script running again\\n\\n| # | Action | Command / Code |\\n|---|--------|----------------|\\n| **1** | Open the file | `code C:\\\\AI_2026\\\\Projects\\\\1_TravelBot\\\\HolidayAgent\\\\Tools\\\\GoogleMap.py` (or your preferred editor) |\\n| **2** | Locate line\u202f13 | Search for `raise HolidayAgentException` |\\n| **3** | Add the missing argument (or use the optional\u2011argument fix) | See the examples above |\\n| **4** | (Optional) Edit the exception class to make `error_detail` optional | Find `class HolidayAgentException` and add `error_detail=None` |\\n| **5** | Save the file |\\n| **6** | Run a quick sanity test (replace with a real API key or a dummy key to hit the error path) | ```python\\\\nfrom Tools.GoogleMap import get_route\\\\ntry:\\\\n    get_route('New+York,NY', 'Boston,MA', 'FAKE_KEY')\\\\nexcept HolidayAgentException as e:\\\\n    print('Caught:', e, '| detail:', e.detail)\\\\n``` |\\n| **7** | Verify no `TypeError` appears and you get a readable error message instead. |\\n| **8** | If you still see the same traceback, search the whole repo for `HolidayAgentException(` to make sure **all** raise statements now supply the second argument (or the class has a default). |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udccc Common pitfalls & how to avoid them  \\n\\n| Pitfall | Why it happens | Fix |\\n|---------|----------------|-----|\\n| **Only one raise statement is fixed** | There may be other `raise HolidayAgentException` calls elsewhere (different modules). | Search the entire project: `grep -R \\\"HolidayAgentException(\\\" .` and update each occurrence. |\\n| **Edited the wrong `HolidayAgentException` class** | The project might have multiple copies (e.g., one in `common/`, another in `tools/`). | Verify the import path in `GoogleMap.py` (`from ..exceptions import HolidayAgentException`). Edit that exact file. |\\n| **Forgot to restart the interpreter** | If you\u2019re running inside a long\u2011living process (e.g., a web server), the old class definition may still be loaded. | Restart the service / interpreter after saving changes. |\\n| **Passing a non\u2011string as `error_detail`** | Some code may inadvertently pass an object that isn\u2019t JSON\u2011serializable when logging later. | Keep `error_detail` as a string (use `str()` if needed). |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## \ud83d\udcde Need more help?\\n\\n* **Show me the exact line 13** (copy\u2011paste it) \u2013 